b><mml:mi>f</mml:mi><mml:mi>B</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msup></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac></mml:mrow></mml:mstyle></mml:mstyle></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:math></disp-formula>
In particular, if <italic>f<sub>A</sub></italic> = <italic>f<sub>B</sub></italic> = 0.5, the mean fraction is <italic>F<sub>NN</sub></italic> = 1/6. This fraction is assessed relative to the complete set of points <italic>N</italic> = <italic>N<sub>A</sub></italic> + <italic>N<sub>B</sub></italic>, i.e. the mean number of pairs of the nearest neighbors is determined as <italic>N</italic>·<italic>F<sub>NN</sub></italic>. The significant bias against frequency (26) is interesting for assessment of trends in natural selection and large-scale genome organization.</p>
